        authenticityMarker: "Filipino farmworkers came to the Salinas Valley beginning in the 1920s, recruited by lettuce growers after Japanese and Chinese labor was restricted; the adobo they made used local wild bay laurel because it was abundant and free, and its use became a regional signature — cooks who moved away from the Salinas Valley have reported that adobo made with Turkish bay tastes 'wrong' compared to the version made with local materials."
