    megaregionId: "california",
    boundsDescription: "The inland delta where the Sacramento and San Joaquin rivers braid through a peat-island archipelago from Sacramento south through Isleton, Walnut Grove, Locke, and Stockton, encompassing the tule marsh remnants, asparagus fields, Bartlett pear orchards, and the Japantown-heritage communities of the historic Chinese and Japanese river towns.",
    culture: "The Sacramento Delta is one of the least-known and most historically dense food cultures in California. Chinese laborers who built the transcontinental railroad and then were barred from urban employment by the Chinese Exclusion Act settled the Delta and built its levee system, establishing the Chinatown of Locke — the only rural Chinatown surviving intact in the United States. Japanese farming families cultivated the peat island soils into the most productive asparagus region in the country until internment in 1942 destroyed that agricultural heritage. The Okies and Arkies who arrived in the Depression-era migration to California brought a Southern BBQ and pit-cooking tradition that fused with the Chinese and Japanese agricultural substrate in unexpected ways.",
    terroir: "Peat island soils of decomposed tule reed, some of the richest organic matter in North America, now mostly below sea level behind earthen levees. The Delta produces Bartlett pears, corn, tomatoes, asparagus, and wine grapes in a foggy, humid microclimate moderated by tidal air movement from the bay. The Sacramento River channel holds striped bass, sturgeon, salmon (in season), and catfish, and the levee banks were historically lined with crawfish burrows worked by Chinese and African American communities. Delta breezes cooling the summer evenings create ideal conditions for Clarksburg's cool-climate wines: Chenin Blanc and Tempranillo grown on the Merritt Island benchland.",
    deviation: "The Delta's food identity is defined by its hidden depth — a place where the physical landscape is invisible to most Californians but where the layering of Chinese levee-labor cooking, Japanese truck-farm produce culture, Southern BBQ pit tradition, and Portuguese river-fishing heritage produces a cuisine that is recognizable from each tradition and reducible to none. The asparagus preparations of the old Japanese farm families — thin-sliced raw with sesame dressing, pickled in rice vinegar and ginger, tempura-fried with lemon salt — were documented before internment and have been partially reconstructed by Delta preservationists. Delta crawfish, smaller and sweeter than Louisiana crawfish, are boiled in a Chinese five-spice and ginger brine unique to the region that reflects the Chinese labor camp cooking of the 1870s. The Isleton Crawdad Festival, held annually since 1977, is the region's primary cultural marker.",
    heirloomIngredients: ["Delta asparagus (grown in peat island soil by descendants of Japanese farming families, available April through June)", "Sacramento River white sturgeon (farmed at Delta aquaculture operations after wild harvest declined, for caviar and smoked flesh)", "Delta crawfish (Procambarus clarkii, boiled in Chinese five-spice ginger brine, available from Delta bait-and-grocery stores in summer)", "Clarksburg Chenin Blanc (from Merritt Island peat and clay soils, floral and honeysuckle-scented, used in poaching and reduction)"],
    iconicDish: "Delta crawfish boil in Chinese five-spice and ginger brine with corn and new potatoes",
    substitutionRule: "Substitute Louisiana crawfish or whole Gulf shrimp for Delta crawfish — the five-spice ginger brine is the defining element, not the crustacean species; Clarksburg Chenin Blanc can be replaced in cooking applications with a dry Vouvray or a neutral Pinot Grigio with a half-teaspoon of honey added per cup to approximate the floral honeysuckle note.",
